\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Linearization of the Two Link Robot Arm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Tarik Tosun, MAE 345 Assignment 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
10/20/11
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
In this assignment, the dynamics of the Type 2 two-link robotics manipulator
 (explored in the previous assignment) were linearized about certain points.
 In doing this, we show the effectiveness of linearization in simplifying
 the analysis of complicated nonlinear dynamic systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Linearization of the State Space Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Derivation of 
\begin_inset Formula $F(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G(t)$
\end_inset

 from State Space Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the first-order linearization of the state space model, we aim to
 express the system in the form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{x\left(t\right)}\thickapprox\mathbf{f}\left[\mathbf{x}_{N}\left(t\right),\mathbf{u}_{N}\left(t\right)\right]+\mathbf{F}\left(t\right)\triangle\mathbf{x}\left(t\right)+\mathbf{G}\left(t\right)\triangle\mathbf{u}\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
Taking the first-order linearization of the state space model, we find:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}\left(t\right)=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
0 & 1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \left.\left(\frac{x_{4}\sin\left(2x_{3}\right)}{\cos^{2}\left(x_{3}\right)}\right)\right|_{eq} & \left.\left(\frac{x_{2}x_{4}\sin\left(2x_{3}\right)+\frac{u_{1}}{ml^{2}}}{\cos^{2}\left(x_{3}\right)}\right)\right|_{eq} & \left.\left(\frac{x_{2}\sin\left(2x_{3}\right)}{\cos^{2}\left(x_{3}\right)}\right)\right|_{eq}\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 1\\
0 & \left.\left(\frac{-\sin\left(2x_{3}\right)}{2}\right)\right|_{eq} & \left.\left(\frac{g}{l}\sin\left(x_{3}\right)-x_{2}\cos\left(2x_{3}\right)\right)\right|_{eq} & 0
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}\left(t\right)=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 0\\
\left.\left(\frac{1}{ml^{2}\cos^{2}\left(x_{3}\right)}\right)\right|_{eq} & 0\\
0 & 0\\
0 & \frac{1}{ml^{2}}
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Constant Conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We wish to determine the circumstances under which 
\series bold
F
\series default
 and 
\series bold
G
\series default
 are constant.
 By inspecting the matrices, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}$
\end_inset

 and, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{4}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}$
\end_inset

 must be constant in order for 
\series bold
F
\series default
 and 
\series bold
G 
\series default
to be constant.
 Both 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 may vary freely.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Analysis about 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{3_{N}}=0^{o},\,\pm45^{o}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We wish to analyze the system under the conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1_{N}}=x_{1_{N}}=$
\end_inset

constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2_{N}}=x_{4_{N}}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2_{N}}=x_{3_{N}}$
\end_inset

 will take on the values 
\begin_inset Formula $-45^{o}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0^{o}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $45^{o}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

