\begin_layout Subsection
Step Response to 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle u_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Please note: Here I am choosing to discuss the response to 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle u_{2}$
\end_inset

 first, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle u_{1}$
\end_inset

 second.
 The system responses to step inputs have been computed and plotted for
 the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle u_{2}$
\end_inset

 given above, and are shown in Figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:pl45_u2_step"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:zero_u2_step"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:min45_u2_step"

\end_inset

.
 In all figures, the step occurs at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1sec$
\end_inset

.
 The step responses illustrate the stability of the system about each of
 the three equilibrium points explored.
 Physically, it corresponds to the instantaneous application of a small
 constant upwards torque at the joint where the transverse arm meets the
 upright link.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3_{N}}=45^{o}$
\end_inset

, we see that the step input quickly drives the system unstable.
 This can be explained in terms of the system's eigenvalues: 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\pm2.63,\,0,\,0$
\end_inset

.
 They are all real, indicating a non-oscillatory response, and one of them
 is positive, indicating instability.
 If a system has even one positive eigenvalue, it will be asymptotically
 unstable- as time increases, the modes of the system goverend by positive
 eigenvalues will grow, while those goverened by negative eigenvalues will
 tend towards zero, causing the unstable modes to dominate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3_{N}}=0^{o}$
\end_inset

, we also see the system's response growing in an unbounded fashion, albeit
 more slowly than for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3_{N}}=45^{o}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, the system's eigenvalues are 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0,\,0,\,0,\,0$
\end_inset

.
 This indicates that the system's dynamics are constant, and its response
 is exactly proportional to the input.
 The angular acceleration of 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

is constant and proportional to the constant input 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle u_{2}$
\end_inset

, so we see 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{4}$
\end_inset

 increasing linearly and 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{3}$
\end_inset

 increasing quadratically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The system's response for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3_{N}}=-45^{o}$
\end_inset

 is quite different from that at either of the other two positions - it
 is stable.
 We see that the system's nonzero eigenvalues are 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\pm2.63i,\,0,\,0$
\end_inset

.
 They are purely imaginary, consistent with constant-amplitude oscillation
 (which is exactly what we see).
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{4}$
\end_inset

 oscillates about zero, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{3}$
\end_inset

 oscillates about position slightly above zero.
 This is point at which the constant input torque and the torque due to
 gravity (accounted for in the system dynamics matrix) are equal.
\end_layout

