\begin_layout Subsection
Step Responses to 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle u_{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The system responses to step inputs have been computed and plotted for the
 values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle u_{1}$
\end_inset

 given above, and are shown in Figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:45_u1_step"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:zero_u1_step"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:min45_u1_step"

\end_inset

.
 As before, the step occurs at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1sec$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The responses can again be explained in terms of the eigenvalues.
 Examining the responses, we see that the third and fourth eigenvalues of
 the dynamics matrices (which take on zero values in all three cases) correspond
 to modes of motion in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 These states exhibit constant dynamics under all three conditions, with
 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{1}$
\end_inset

 increasing linearly and 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{2}$
\end_inset

 increasing quatratically.
 However,
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{4}$
\end_inset

 (and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{3}$
\end_inset

) is coupled to 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{2}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2_{N}}=x_{3_{N}}\neq0^{o}$
\end_inset

, so under these conditions we would expect to see exponential and oscillatory
 responses in 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{4}$
\end_inset

.
 Inspecting the figures, that is exactly what we see.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2_{N}}=45^{o}$
\end_inset

, we see exponential growth in 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{4}$
\end_inset

 due to the real positive eigenvalue that governs their behavior under these
 conditions.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2_{N}}=-45^{o}$
\end_inset

, we see a purely oscillatory response in 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{4}$
\end_inset

, and an oscillatory but increasing response in 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 There is motion on two time scales here.
 On the slow time scale, we see the 'equilibrium angle' of the transverse
 arm (the angle at which the gravitational and centripital torques are equal)
 increase linearly with increasing angular velocity.
 On the fast time scale, we see oscillations about this 'equilibrium angle'
 due to the oscillatory mode of the first two imaginary eigenvalues.
 For 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $x_{3_{N}}=0^{o}$
\end_inset

, the first two states are decoupled from the second two states, so we see
 no response in 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle x_{4}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

