\begin_layout Section
Effects of Constant Angular Rate About Vertical Axis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}_{1}=x_{2_{N}}$
\end_inset

takes on constant values between 
\begin_inset Formula $0^{o}/sec$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $720^{o}/sec$
\end_inset

.
 We wish to determine the effect of this nominal angular rate on the eigenvalues
 of 
\series bold
F
\series default
 under the three conditions previously explored.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:zero_eig"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:p45_eig"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:min45_eig"

\end_inset

 show plots of the real and imaginary part of the eigenvalues for each of
 the three cases explored as 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}_{1}=x_{2_{N}}$
\end_inset

 varies between 
\begin_inset Formula $0^{o}/sec$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $720^{o}/sec$
\end_inset

.
 The rotation of the upright introduces a centripetal force which changes
 the values of the first two eigenvalues, which control the dynamics of
 the transverse arm.
 We begin by investigating 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:zero_eig"

\end_inset

, showing the zero degree case.
 We see that the centripital force introduces an oscillatory mode into the
 system, as evidenced by the pure imaginary eigenvalues that grow with the
 square root of the angular rate.
 This makes physical sense, as the centripetal force will act as a restoring
 moment towards the equilibrium point of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}=x_{3}=0^{o}$
\end_inset

.
 The force acts in the horizontal direction and its moment arm is proportional
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\left(\theta_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, so we expect to see an oscillatory mode analogous to that of a simple
 pendulum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm45^{o}$
\end_inset

 cases, we see similar effects.
 In both 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:p45_eig"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:min45_eig"

\end_inset

 we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}_{1}\thickapprox400^{o}/sec$
\end_inset

 appears to be a special point - in the 
\begin_inset Formula $45^{o}$
\end_inset

case, the eigenvalues switch from being entirely real to all zero to entirely
 imaginary at this point, and in the 
\begin_inset Formula $-45^{o}$
\end_inset

 case the imaginary eigenvalues suddenly cross through zero.
 This angular velocity corresponds to the point at which the centripetal
 torque exactly balances the gravitational torque for the moment arm correspondi
ng to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm45^{o}$
\end_inset

.
 For rotations slower than 
\begin_inset Formula $400^{o}/sec$
\end_inset

, gravitational effects dominate.
 In the 
\begin_inset Formula $45^{o}$
\end_inset

 case, this means the system is unstable, for reasons discussed in the previous
 assignment - the torque required to balance gravity decreases with increasing
 angle, so perturbations lead to unbounded growth.
 In the 
\begin_inset Formula $-45^{o}$
\end_inset

 case, the system is stable and oscillatory, and becomes more oscillatory
 with increasing angular velocity because the centripital force acts as
 an additional restoring torque.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $400^{o}/sec$
\end_inset

, gravity and the centripetal force are perfectly balanced, so all eigenvalues
 are zero.
 For rotations faster than 
\begin_inset Formula $400^{o}/sec$
\end_inset

, the centripetal effects dominate.
 In the 
\begin_inset Formula $-45^{o}$
\end_inset

 case, the system is still stable, and the oscillatory imaginary eigenvalues
 continue to increase with angular velocity at the same rate as before.
 For the 
\begin_inset Formula $45^{o}$
\end_inset

 case however, the system dynamics have changed - the overall torque now
 acts as a restoring torque, and we have oscillatory imaginary eigenvalues.
\end_layout

