\begin_layout Section*
Conclusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results of these analyses show that important qualities of dynamic systems
 (such as stability to perturbation) can often be accurately determined
 through linearization about points of interest.
 Linearization can simplify the mathematics required to analyze a complicated
 nonlinear system a great deal, making it a very useful tool in the study
 of dynamic systems.
 It is important to note, however, that these results are valid 
\shape italic
only in the vicinity of the linearization point.
 
\shape default
For example, our linearized equations about 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2_{N}}=-45^{o}$
\end_inset

indicate that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

 will increase linearly with increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}_{1}$
\end_inset

 for arbitrarily large values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Physically, this is quite incorrect - 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

 may only increase until it reaches 
\begin_inset Formula $0^{o}$
\end_inset

.
 While linearization is a powerful tool, we must be careful to apply linearized
 equations only where they are valid.
\end_layout

\end_body
